post_text:
Last night, eight Landry-Walker seniors earned college credentials from Nunez Community College, after just receiving their high school diplomas last Monday!
Through a partnership Landry-Walker has formed with the Urban League of Louisiana Project Ready dual enrollment program, two of the graduates earned Associate of Applied Science degrees in industrial technology, while the other six completed the Certificate of Technical Studies in Welding or Electrical Construction. These students have worked hard to earn industry recognized credentials, which provides them with an opportunity to be competitive for lucrative careers or college success.

Congrats to:
‚Ä¢Kevin Wilson- AAS Industrial Technology
‚Ä¢Jomyra Mathis- AAS Industrial Technology
‚Ä¢Theronae Armstrong- CTS Electrical
‚Ä¢Mya Cooley- CTS Electrical
‚Ä¢Bryan McMillian- CTS Electrical
‚Ä¢Fred Gilbert- CTS Welding
‚Ä¢Juan Matthews- CTS Welding
‚Ä¢Nolan Nunnery- CTS Welding

Algiers Charter

Landry-Walker 9th and 10th graders took Aptitude Tests today. The Aptitude Test is an online skills assessment that allows students to explore options and interests in future careers. Based on their interest and skills, students are presented with three possible areas of career interests. The assessment is used to help Landry-Walker counselors assist students in determining their educational track for a jump start in their career training.

post_text:
Last night, the Landry-Walker Marching Band performed at the Washington Mardi Gras Ball in Washington, D.C.
Landry-Walker was the only marching band to perform and the 1st high school band to ever participate in this annual event.
While there, they visited many of our nation's historic monuments and memorials.
Congrats to these talented students for positively representing Landry-Walker, the State of Louisiana, the City of New Orleans, and the Algiers community!

Algiers Charter
December 3, 2015 at 9:20 AM ¬∑

Stopbullying.gov reported "bullying can lead to or worsen feelings of isolation, rejection, exclusion, and despair, as well as depression and anxiety, which can contribute to suicidal behavior."

Theater students at LB Landry - OP Walker College and Career Preparatory High School wrote and performed a play about the impacts bullying for the 3rd-8th grade students at William J. Fischer Accelerated Academy. The messge was clear- bullying is painful and impacts people even more than what you see at school.

shared_text:
Algiers Charter
November 17, 2015 at 2:53 PM ¬∑

Do you know how to protect yourself from identity fraud?

Students at LB Landry - OP Walker College and Career Preparatory High School kicked off a financial literacy program in partnership with Whitney Bank last week. Topics during the presentation included identity fraud, student loan debt, and mobile banking. Seniors will participate in the online Whitney Bank Financial Cents program throughout the school year.

Louisiana Association of Public Charter Schools
December 2, 2015 at 12:35 PM ¬∑

Congrats to the 10 Louisiana charter schools awarded grants from the Louisiana Department of Education to support career prep & opportunities for students with disabilities!

The recipients are Darbonne Woods Charter School, Louisiana Connections Academy, Dr. Martin Luther King Charter School for Science & Technology, LB Landry - OP Walker College and Career Preparatory High School, Algiers Technology Academy, Sophie B Wright, KIPP Renaissance High School, Cohen College Prep, ReNEW Schools, and Sci Academy.
